<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>The <code>cite</code> <strong>attribute</strong> provides a URL pointing to the source document for quoted or edited content. It is a purely semantic annotation — browsers do not display the URL, and no link is created. The value is intended for search engines, content scrapers, and other tooling that processes structured content.</p>
<p><strong>Important:</strong> This page documents the <code>cite</code> <em>attribute</em>, not the <a href="/docs/elements/native/cite/"><code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> element</a>. They serve different purposes.</p>
<p><strong>Applies to:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li><code>&lt;blockquote&gt;</code> — URL of the original source being quoted</li>
  <li><code>&lt;del&gt;</code> — URL of the document explaining the deletion</li>
  <li><code>&lt;ins&gt;</code> — URL of the document explaining the insertion</li>
</ul>

<h2>Values</h2>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Element</th><th>cite Value</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><code>&lt;blockquote&gt;</code></td><td>URL</td><td>The source of the quoted text</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&lt;del&gt;</code></td><td>URL</td><td>A document explaining the removal</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&lt;ins&gt;</code></td><td>URL</td><td>A document explaining the addition</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Blockquote Attribution</h2>
<p>Use the <code>cite</code> attribute to record where a quote came from. Since browsers do not display it, always pair it with visible attribution for human readers.</p>

